## 0.9) Frontend Stack & Edge Protection (KRITISKT - LÄRDOMEN FRÅN MIDDLEWARE-FELET)

### THE FUNDAMENTAL RULE

**This is a Vite + React SPA (Single Page Application), NOT Next.js.**

This means:
- ❌ **NO server-side middleware support** (Vite builds pure client-side apps)
- ❌ **NO `middleware.ts` with Next.js syntax** (`NextRequest`/`NextResponse` does not exist)
- ❌ **NO server-side rendering (SSR)** by default (client-only rendering)
- ✅ **Edge protection MUST use alternative approaches** (Vercel config, Cloudflare, or backend-only)

### Tech Stack Reality Check

```json
// package.json (THE SOURCE OF TRUTH)
{
  "name": "vite_react_shadcn_ts",  // ← VITE, not Next.js!
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "vite",                  // ← Uses Vite dev server
    "build": "vite build"           // ← Builds client-side bundle
  }
}
```

**What this means:**
- Frontend is **100% client-side** (runs in browser, not on server)
- No server-side code execution (no middleware, no API routes, no SSR)
- All data fetching happens via Supabase client (PostgREST API)

### Common Mistake: Trying to Add Next.js Middleware

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: This will NOT work in Vite
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  // This code will never run - Vite has no middleware support!
  return NextResponse.next();
}
```

**Error you'll get:**
- `Cannot find module 'next/server'` (Next.js is not installed)
- File is ignored during Vite build (no middleware concept exists)

### Correct Patterns for Edge Protection in Vite

#### Pattern 1: Vercel Config (Security Headers Only)

```json
// vercel.json
{
  "headers": [
    {
      "source": "/(.*)",
      "headers": [
        { "key": "X-Content-Type-Options", "value": "nosniff" },
        { "key": "X-Frame-Options", "value": "DENY" },
        { "key": "X-XSS-Protection", "value": "1; mode=block" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

**Pros:**
- ✅ Works with Vite (Vercel handles at CDN level)
- ✅ No code changes needed
- ✅ Basic security headers

**Cons:**
- ⚠️ No bot detection (just headers)
- ⚠️ No rate limiting (unless Vercel Pro)
- ⚠️ No custom logic

#### Pattern 2: Cloudflare (Bot Detection + Rate Limiting)

**Setup:** Point domain to Cloudflare → Enable bot detection

**Pros:**
- ✅ Works with any SPA (including Vite)
- ✅ Free tier includes bot detection
- ✅ DDoS protection included
- ✅ Rate limiting available

**Cons:**
- ⚠️ Requires DNS change
- ⚠️ Learning curve for Cloudflare dashboard

#### Pattern 3: Backend-Only Protection (Current Implementation)

**Rely on existing strong backend security:**
- ✅ Hard limits: 50-100 items/request (server-side in RPC functions)
- ✅ RLS on all tables
- ✅ `api_public` schema isolation
- ✅ Hashed IDs (`segment_hash`)
- ✅ SECURITY INVOKER/DEFINER patterns

**Pros:**
- ✅ Already implemented and working
- ✅ No additional infrastructure needed
- ✅ Sufficient for initial launch

**Cons:**
- ⚠️ No edge-level bot detection
- ⚠️ Bots reach backend (but are rate-limited there)

#### Pattern 4: Client-Side Honeypots (Telemetry)

```tsx
// src/components/Layout.tsx
<a 
  href="/api/do-not-follow" 
  style={{ position: 'absolute', left: '-9999px' }}
  aria-hidden="true"
  tabIndex={-1}
>
  Admin Panel
</a>
```

**Pros:**
- ✅ Works in Vite (pure HTML)
- ✅ Helps identify bots (they follow hidden links)
- ✅ Can log to analytics

**Cons:**
- ⚠️ Detection only (no blocking)
- ⚠️ Requires backend logic to act on flagged IPs

#### Pattern 5: Vercel Rewrites (Sitemap & Share Proxy)

**Sitemap:** `/sitemap.xml` is rewritten to the Supabase Edge Function `sitemap` so crawlers get a dynamic XML (news, chronicles, static pages). Static `public/sitemap.xml` is not used in production.

```json
// vercel.json rewrites
{
  "rewrites": [
    { "source": "/sitemap.xml", "destination": "https://niacajcdefleobqtyrmi.supabase.co/functions/v1/sitemap" },
    { "source": "/share/chronicle/:slug", "destination": "https://niacajcdefleobqtyrmi.supabase.co/functions/v1/share-proxy?type=chronicle&id=:slug" },
    { "source": "/share/news/:id", "destination": "https://niacajcdefleobqtyrmi.supabase.co/functions/v1/share-proxy?type=news&id=:id" }
  ]
}
```

**robots.txt:** Served from `public/robots.txt`; MUST include `Sitemap: https://aikurerad.se/sitemap.xml`. Allow `User-agent: *` and `Allow: /` for crawlers.

**Requirements:** See requirements.mdc §R10 (SEO & Discovery).

### Migration Path: Vite → Next.js (If Needed)

**When to consider migration:**
- Need server-side rendering (SSR) for SEO
- Need API routes (backend endpoints)
- Need middleware (edge-level bot detection)
- Want built-in optimizations (image optimization, etc.)

**Migration complexity:** High (2-3 days)
- Routing changes (file-based → App Router)
- Build config changes (vite.config.ts → next.config.js)
- Component updates (client vs server components)

**Recommendation:** Stay on Vite unless SSR/middleware becomes critical business need.

### Do/Don't Summary

❌ **NEVER:**
- Create `middleware.ts` with Next.js syntax in Vite project
- Import from `'next/server'` or `'next/*'`
- Assume server-side code execution exists
- Copy middleware examples from Next.js docs

✅ **ALWAYS:**
- Check `package.json` to verify stack (Vite vs Next.js)
- Use Vercel config for headers (if on Vercel)
- Consider Cloudflare for bot detection (if critical)
- Rely on backend security as primary defense

### Security Model Summary

**Current Stack (Vite + Supabase):**
```
Browser → Vercel CDN → Static HTML/JS/CSS
                ↓
        Supabase PostgREST API
                ↓
        RLS + Limits + Schema Isolation
```

**If Migrated to Next.js:**
```
Browser → Vercel Edge → Next.js Middleware (bot detection)
                           ↓
                     Next.js SSR/API Routes
                           ↓
                  Supabase PostgREST API
                           ↓
              RLS + Limits + Schema Isolation
```

